[[File:Haleets Rock survey marks.jpg|thumb|Closeup showing 19th century [[survey marker|survey marks]] on Haleets Rock. The letters "C S" ([[Coast Survey]]) can be seen nearly inverted.]]
'''Haleets''' (also called '''Figurehead Rock''') is a sandstone [[glacial erratic]] boulder{{sfn|Casey|2012|p=126}}{{sfn|Lewarch|2012|p=3}} with inscribed [[petroglyph]]s on [[Bainbridge Island, Washington]]. The Native American [[Suquamish Tribe]] claims the rock, on a public beach at [[Agate Point, Bainbridge Island, Washington|Agate Point]] on the shore of [[Agate Passage]], as part of their heritage.{{sfn|Lewarch|2012|p=3}} The exact date the petroglyphs were carved is unknown but is estimated to be around 1000 BCE to 400 or 500 CE, the latest date being when [[labret]]s (worn by one of the petroglyph figures) were no longer used by Coast Salish peoples.{{sfn|Bainbridge Island Historical Museum|2012}}{{sfn|Leen|2015}}

Haleets is the [[Coast Salish]] name of the rock, also transcrbed as Halelos, Xalelos and Xalilc, meaning "marked face".{{sfn|Alcalá|2013}} It is known in English as Figurehead Rock. Its purpose is unknown but the [[Suquamish Museum]] curator and archivist Charlie Sigo has stated that it may have been a boundary marker.{{sfn|Westbrook|1999}} An [[amateur astronomer]] has proposed a theory that it has a calendrical function (see [[Archaeoastronomy]]).{{sfn|Lewarch|2012|p=3}}{{sfn|Westbrook|1999}}{{sfn|Bainbridge Island Review|2008}}{{refn|group=notes|Bainbridge Island Historical Museum 2012: "The petroglyph lies precisely west of the [[Sky Valley Washington|Skykomish canyon]] 60 miles away. Standing at the petroglyph on the vernal and autumnal equinox, one can view the rising sun shining straight through the canyon."{{sfn|Bainbridge Island Historical Museum|2012}}}}

The rock is {{convert|5|ft}} tall and {{convert|7|ft}} long. It sits about {{convert|100|ft}} offshore,{{sfn|Westbrook|1999}} and has been marked with chiseled and drilled coast survey features since 1856, and a bronze [[geodetic mark]] was placed on it in 1934.{{sfn|NOAA|2015}} Some sources say that the rock is one of three prominent Salish Sea petroglyphs that were always on the shoreline,{{sfn|Beauchamp|2013}} but tectonic activity around the [[Seattle Fault]] may have put Haleets in the intertidal zone.{{refn|group=notes|Alcalá 2013: "Within human memory, Laxelks, now called [[Wing Point, Bainbridge Island, Washington|Wing Point]], fell about three feet during an earthquake."{{sfn|Alcalá|2013}}}}

